abstract = {This paper outlines the introduction of computer technology in the Austrian IFF (Interuniversitaeres Forschungsinstitut fuer Fernstudien/Research Institute for study programs by correspondence and adult education). This institute was founded and is presided by several Austrian universities, but independent in its administration and research activities. Moreover, it consists of six relatively autonomous research departments and study centres all over Austria, each of them having its own research and educational priorities and its own management structure. The paper is concerned with the specific strategies of computer introduction in this university organization (e.g. user's participation, training methods,bottom-up-automation). It also deals with the conflicts and problems which have occurred since the beginning of computer implementation. The conflicts in particular illustrate clearly the role of the computer as a cataclyst for organisational problems within a management structure. The case study explores the question how the centralized introduction of computer technologies in a decentralized structure can be managed so as to develop and put into practice a viable concept of end user computing.}
}
@article{KATSOULAKOS2016174,
